{"seeAlsoSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-structs-and-unions-in-swift","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-functions-in-swift","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-macros-in-swift"],"anchor":"Language-Interoperability-with-C-and-C++","title":"Language Interoperability with C and C++","generated":true}],"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"major":0,"patch":0},"sections":[],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift"]]},"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"anchor":"Overview","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Because structures in C can’t have methods, property accessors, or custom initializers,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"you often need to write such functionality using global functions. Structures in"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Swift can declare methods, property accessors, and initializers. You use the "},{"code":"CF_SWIFT_NAME","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"macro to group together related global functions into a single structure type that’s"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"imported into Swift."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Apply-CFSWIFTNAME-to-Related-Functions","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Apply CF_SWIFT_NAME to Related Functions"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The example below shows several functions that are all related to a "},{"code":"Color","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" type."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"code":"CF_SWIFT_NAME","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" macro is applied to each function, giving each one a new name"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for Swift that’s nested together under the "},{"code":"Color","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" type:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["Color ColorCreateWithCMYK(float c, float m, float y, float k) CF_SWIFT_NAME(Color.init(c:m:y:k:));","","float ColorGetHue(Color color) CF_SWIFT_NAME(getter:Color.hue(self:));","void ColorSetHue(Color color, float hue) CF_SWIFT_NAME(setter:Color.hue(self:newValue:));","","Color ColorDarkenColor(Color color, float amount) CF_SWIFT_NAME(Color.darken(self:amount:));","","extern const Color ColorBondiBlue CF_SWIFT_NAME(Color.bondiBlue);","","Color ColorGetCalibrationColor(void) CF_SWIFT_NAME(getter:Color.calibration());","Color ColorSetCalibrationColor(Color color) CF_SWIFT_NAME(setter:Color.calibration(newValue:));"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"occ"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The argument you pass to the "},{"code":"CF_SWIFT_NAME","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" macro uses the same syntax as the "},{"code":"#selector","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"expression. You use "},{"code":"self","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" in a "},{"code":"CF_SWIFT_NAME","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" argument to refer to the instance"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"that the method belongs to."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Import-Related-Functions-into-Swift","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Import Related Functions into Swift"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Here’s how Swift imports the related functions above into a single type:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["extension Color {","    init(c: Float, m: Float, y: Float, k: Float)","","    var hue: Float { get set }","","    func darken(amount: Float) -> Color","","    static var bondiBlue: Color","","    static var calibration: Color","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"name":"Note","style":"note","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can’t reorder or change the number of arguments for type members imported"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"using the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"CF_SWIFT_NAME"},{"type":"text","text":" macro."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"aside"}],"kind":"content"}],"kind":"article","identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/customizing-your-c-code-for-swift"},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Use the "},{"code":"CF_SWIFT_NAME","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" macro to group functions that have related behavior."}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/swift\/customizing-your-c-code-for-swift"]}],"metadata":{"roleHeading":"Article","modules":[{"name":"Swift"}],"role":"article","title":"Customizing Your C Code for Swift"},"references":{"doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift/using-imported-c-macros-in-swift":{"url":"\/documentation\/swift\/using-imported-c-macros-in-swift","title":"Using Imported C Macros in Swift","type":"topic","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Use imported C-defined macros as constants."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-macros-in-swift","kind":"article"},"doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift/using-imported-c-structs-and-unions-in-swift":{"url":"\/documentation\/swift\/using-imported-c-structs-and-unions-in-swift","kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-structs-and-unions-in-swift","title":"Using Imported C Structs and Unions in Swift","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Learn how Swift represents imported C structures and unions, including types with"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"bitfields and unnamed fields."}],"type":"topic","role":"article"},"doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swift","role":"collection","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"text":"Build apps using a powerful open language.","type":"text"}],"title":"Swift"},"doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift/using-imported-c-functions-in-swift":{"kind":"article","title":"Using Imported C Functions in Swift","abstract":[{"text":"Learn how to call imported functions that are declared in a C header.","type":"text"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-functions-in-swift","role":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swift\/using-imported-c-functions-in-swift","type":"topic"}}}